What is APR?APR stands for Annual Percentage Rate. It's a measure used to compare the yearly cost of borrowing or earning money in financial products such as loans, mortgages, savings accounts, or credit cards. The APR includes not only the interest rate but also any additional fees or costs associated with the transaction.

For example, if you're taking out a loan and the lender charges an origination fee, those fees are included in the APR calculation. This gives you a more comprehensive understanding of the total cost of borrowing over one year.

On the other hand, when it comes to savings accounts or investments, the APR represents the annual rate at which your money will grow. The higher the APR, the more quickly your money will increase in value.

It's important to note that while APR can be a useful tool for comparing different financial products, it doesn't tell the whole story. Other factors like compounding frequency and whether fees are upfront or rolled into the loan balance can also affect the total cost of borrowing or earning interest.yes
